export const story = {"seriesId":"the-girl-who-was-accidentally-betrothed-to-a-dragon","storyId":"the-girl-who-was-accidentally-betrothed-to-a-dragon","storyKey":"the-girl-who-was-accidentally-betrothed-to-a-dragon/the-girl-who-was-accidentally-betrothed-to-a-dragon","seriesTitle":"The Girl Who Was Accidentally Betrothed to a Dragon","seriesDescription":"Due to a clerical error in the Royal Betrothal Office, Lady Wren Fitzgerald has been legally engaged to a dragon since birth. The dragon is equally horrified.","title":"The Girl Who Was Accidentally Betrothed to a Dragon","author":"Roughdraft Stories","description":"Due to a clerical error in the Royal Betrothal Office, Lady Wren Fitzgerald has been legally engaged to a dragon since birth. The dragon is equally horrified.","ageRange":"8-12","genre":"Fantasy Comedy","tags":["humor","dragons","bureaucracy","adventure","friendship"],"coverImage":null,"chapters":[{"id":1,"number":1,"title":"The Invitation List","file":"chapter-1.md","markdown":"# The Invitation List\n\nThe year that Lady Wren Fitzgerald turned seventeen, she was the fourteenth most eligible young woman in the kingdom of Briarwell. This was a significant improvement from the previous year, when she had ranked twenty-third, largely due to her unfortunate habit of correcting adults about beetles.\n\n\"That's not a ladybug,\" she had told the Duchess of Pemberton at last year's Spring Ball. \"That's a *Harmonia axyridis*, the Asian lady beetle. You can tell by the M-shaped marking on the pronotum. Ladybugs have spots that are more—\"\n\nThe Duchess had walked away somewhere around \"pronotum.\"\n\nBut by seventeen, Wren had learned (mostly) to keep her beetle observations to herself, and her ranking had improved accordingly. Not that Wren cared about rankings. Wren cared about beetles, and about being left alone, and about her collection of mounted specimens that took up three entire rooms of the east wing, much to her mother's despair.\n\n\"You could use those rooms for *embroidery*,\" Lady Fitzgerald often said.\n\n\"I could,\" Wren agreed. \"I won't, but I could.\"\n\nThe trouble began, as troubles often do, with an administrative error.\n\nTo understand what happened, you must first understand the Royal Betrothal Office, which has existed in Briarwell for four hundred and twenty-seven years and has, in that time, accumulated a reputation for legendary incompetence. The Office occupies the third floor of the Palace's east wing, where seventeen clerks work very slowly on matters of tremendous importance.\n\nThe most famous error in the Office's history occurred in 1847, when a clerk named Marmaduke Pennywhistle accidentally betrothed a countess to a particularly nice hat. (The hat was the property of Viscount Alderton, who was quite attached to it, and the resulting legal battle lasted seven years. The countess eventually won custody of the hat on alternate weekends.) Other notable errors include the Great Misfiling of 1862, in which forty-three betrothals were recorded using invisible ink (they had run out of the regular kind), and the unfortunate incident of 1901, when a clerk's pet ferret ate an entire drawer of pending applications.\n\nBut none of these errors quite compared to what Marmaduke Pennywhistle's great-great-grandson, also named Marmaduke Pennywhistle (the family lacked imagination), did on the day of Wren's birth.\n\nWren's parents had, like all noble families, submitted a Preliminary Betrothal Interest Form within hours of her birth. This was standard practice. The form was simple: it stated that Lord and Lady Fitzgerald wished to register their daughter for future betrothal consideration, and it requested a match with any suitable party of noble standing, good character, and reasonable proximity.\n\nThe elder Marmaduke Pennywhistle had processed thousands of such forms without incident. The younger Marmaduke, however, had recently taken up a hobby.\n\nThe hobby was exotic fauna.\n\nOn the particular day when Wren's form arrived, young Marmaduke was reading a fascinating treatise on the social habits of dragons. Dragons, he had learned, were not the fire-breathing terrors of legend, but rather scholarly creatures who lived in the Ashenmount Mountains and spent most of their time arguing about geology. They had their own universities, their own tenure committees, and their own rather complicated marriage customs.\n\n\"How interesting,\" Marmaduke had muttered, turning a page with one hand while reaching for the next form in his pile with the other.\n\nHe had stamped the form without looking.\n\nHe had filed it without reading.\n\nAnd he had, in doing so, betrothed the newborn Lady Wren Fitzgerald to \"Cornelius, of the Ashenmount Estate\"—a dragon who was, at that very moment, defending his dissertation on volcanic mineral deposits to a panel of extremely critical elder dragons.\n\nCornelius had not been consulted about this arrangement.\n\nNeither, for that matter, had Wren's parents.\n\nThe form had simply... vanished into the vast paper wilderness of the Royal Betrothal Office, where it remained undisturbed for seventeen years, until someone thought to look up the invitation list for Wren's eighteenth birthday celebration.\n\n\"Mother,\" Wren said, looking up from the draft invitation list that had been placed on her breakfast plate. \"Why is there a dragon on my guest list?\"\n\nLady Fitzgerald was arranging flowers and did not turn around. \"Don't be silly, dear. There's no dragon on your guest list.\"\n\n\"There is. Right here. 'Cornelius of Ashenmount, the betrothed.'\" Wren frowned. \"What does 'the betrothed' mean?\"\n\nThe vase Lady Fitzgerald was holding made a sound that vases should not make when they hit the floor.\n\n\"Let me see that,\" Lady Fitzgerald said, in a voice that had gone very quiet and very careful.\n\nWren handed over the list.\n\nThere was a long silence.\n\n\"Harold!\" Lady Fitzgerald called, in the voice she used when someone was about to be in considerable trouble. \"HAROLD!\"\n\nLord Fitzgerald appeared in the doorway, looking alarmed. He had been in his study, doing whatever it was that lords did in studies (Wren suspected it involved napping, but she couldn't prove it). \"What is it? What's happened? Is something on fire?\"\n\n\"Nothing is on fire. Yet.\" Lady Fitzgerald thrust the paper at him. \"Explain this.\"\n\nLord Fitzgerald read the paper. His face went through several interesting colors.\n\n\"Ah,\" he said.\n\n\"'Ah'? That's all you have to say? *Ah*?\"\n\n\"Well, I'm sure there's a reasonable explanation—\"\n\n\"Our daughter is betrothed to a DRAGON, Harold!\"\n\n\"Perhaps it's a typo?\"\n\n\"A typo of what? What word could they possibly have meant that came out as DRAGON?\"\n\nLord Fitzgerald thought about this. \"Wagon?\"\n\n\"She's not betrothed to a WAGON either!\"\n\nWren, who had been watching this exchange with growing interest, raised a hand. \"I have a question.\"\n\nBoth parents turned to look at her.\n\n\"Is this legally binding?\"\n\nAnother silence, this one even longer than the first.\n\n\"I'll send for the lawyers,\" Lord Fitzgerald said quietly, and left the room.\n\nThe lawyers arrived at noon. There were three of them, all wearing identical expressions of barely suppressed horror.\n\n\"It's... unprecedented,\" said the first lawyer.\n\n\"It's quite irregular,\" said the second lawyer.\n\n\"It's completely valid,\" said the third lawyer, who was the most junior and therefore the most honest. \"According to the Betrothal Registry Act of 1723, any agreement filed and stamped by an authorized clerk of the Royal Betrothal Office is legally binding upon both parties, their heirs, and their estates, in perpetuity.\"\n\n\"But one of the parties is a DRAGON,\" Lady Fitzgerald said.\n\n\"The Act does not specify species,\" the third lawyer said, flipping through a very old book. \"It merely requires that both parties be 'of sound mind and reasonable estate.' Dragons, as it happens, are quite wealthy. Something about sitting on hoards of gold. And the Ashenmount dragons are known to be particularly sound of mind—one of them won the Briarwell Prize for Mathematics last year.\"\n\n\"Surely there must be some way to dissolve this arrangement,\" Lord Fitzgerald said.\n\nThe lawyers exchanged looks.\n\n\"There is... one possibility,\" the first lawyer admitted. \"But it would require the approval of the Office's Senior Clerk. A woman named Ms. Parchment.\"\n\n\"Then let's contact her immediately!\"\n\n\"She's on holiday. She takes her annual leave very seriously. She won't be back for three weeks.\"\n\n\"THREE WEEKS?\"\n\n\"She's visiting her sister in the Outer Isles. There's no way to reach her.\"\n\nWren, who had been silent through most of this, stood up. \"Excuse me.\"\n\nEveryone turned to look at her.\n\n\"While you're all panicking,\" she said, \"has anyone thought to ask the dragon how he feels about this?\"\n\nThe lawyers stared. Her parents stared. Nobody, it seemed, had considered this.\n\n\"Because if I've learned anything from cataloging beetles,\" Wren continued, \"it's that you shouldn't assume things about a creature until you've actually observed it. For all we know, the dragon is just as horrified as we are.\" She paused. \"Probably more. I've heard dragons are very particular about protocol.\"\n\n\"You can't just... go talk to a dragon,\" Lady Fitzgerald said.\n\n\"Why not?\"\n\n\"It's... it's not DONE.\"\n\n\"Neither is accidentally being betrothed to one, but here we are.\" Wren folded her arms. \"I'm going to Ashenmount. I'm going to find this Cornelius. And I'm going to sort this out.\"\n\nLord Fitzgerald opened his mouth, probably to object.\n\nWren fixed him with the look she used on particularly stubborn beetle specimens.\n\nHe closed his mouth.\n\n\"Take the carriage,\" he said weakly. \"And maybe a guard. Or twelve.\"\n\n\"I'll take one guard,\" Wren said. \"And my specimen bag. If I'm going to the Ashenmount Mountains, I might as well collect some volcanic beetles.\"\n\nAnd that, as they say, is how the adventure began—with a clerical error, a missed checkbox, and a seventeen-year-old girl who was considerably more practical than anyone gave her credit for.\n\nThe dragon, as it turned out, was about to have a very bad day.\n\nBut then again, so was Wren.\n","narration":null},{"id":2,"number":2,"title":"The Meeting","file":"chapter-2.md","markdown":"# The Meeting\n\nThe Ashenmount Mountains were, as mountains go, rather more dramatic than strictly necessary. They loomed. They brooded. They were perpetually wreathed in a kind of moody mist that seemed designed specifically to make travelers feel unwelcome.\n\nWren found them fascinating.\n\n\"Look at that basalt formation,\" she said, pressing her face against the carriage window. \"The columnar jointing is magnificent. I bet there are Buprestidae beetles in there. The metallic wood-borers love volcanic rock.\"\n\nThe guard, whose name was Bernard and who had been chosen for this mission primarily because he was the only one who hadn't pretended to be sick, said nothing. Bernard had learned in the first hour of the journey that Lady Wren did not require responses to her observations about beetles. She would simply continue making them whether anyone was listening or not.\n\nThe carriage wound its way up a narrow mountain path, past warning signs that became increasingly urgent.\n\nDRAGON TERRITORY AHEAD.\n\nNO TRESPASSING.\n\nSERIOUSLY, TURN AROUND.\n\nTHIS MEANS YOU.\n\nFINE, BUT DON'T SAY WE DIDN'T WARN YOU.\n\n\"Friendly,\" Wren remarked.\n\nThe path ended at an enormous cave entrance, flanked by two statues of dragons in what appeared to be academic regalia—tiny stone mortarboards perched on their heads, stone scrolls clutched in their claws. A sign hung between them:\n\nASHENMOUNT UNIVERSITY\nDEPARTMENT OF GEOLOGICAL STUDIES\nVISITORS PLEASE CHECK IN AT RECEPTION\n\n\"It's a university,\" Bernard said, sounding both relieved and confused.\n\n\"Of course it is. Dragons are scholars. Everyone knows that.\" Wren climbed out of the carriage and straightened her traveling cloak. \"Wait here. I shouldn't be long.\"\n\n\"My lady, I really should accompany—\"\n\n\"If I need someone to stand around looking confused, I'll call you.\"\n\nShe left Bernard sputtering and walked into the cave.\n\nThe interior was not what she expected. She had imagined dark tunnels, perhaps some dramatic torchlight, maybe a skeleton or two for atmosphere. Instead, she found herself in a well-lit atrium with polished stone floors and a reception desk staffed by a very small dragon wearing spectacles.\n\n\"Can I help you?\" the small dragon asked, not looking up from the pile of paperwork in front of him.\n\n\"I'm looking for Cornelius of Ashenmount.\"\n\n\"Which one?\"\n\nWren blinked. \"There's more than one?\"\n\nThe small dragon finally looked up. His spectacles magnified his eyes to approximately the size of dinner plates. \"There are forty-seven Corneliuses currently enrolled or employed at this institution. It's a very popular name among dragons. Traditional. Dignified. Bit boring, if you ask me, but nobody does.\" He peered at her. \"You're a human.\"\n\n\"Yes.\"\n\n\"We don't get many of those. Are you here for a conference?\"\n\n\"I'm here because I'm apparently betrothed to one of your Corneliuses. The paperwork says 'Cornelius of Ashenmount Estate.' That's all I have to go on.\"\n\nThe small dragon stared at her for a long moment. Then he burst out laughing.\n\nIt was a strange sound, like someone had put gravel in a bellows and was operating it enthusiastically. The dragon laughed so hard that his spectacles fell off and clattered onto the desk.\n\n\"Oh, that's WONDERFUL,\" he wheezed. \"Someone finally filed the paperwork against old Cornelius! He's been dodging the Betrothal Office for centuries! I mean, not that I blame him—have you seen the forms? Absolute nightmare. But still!\" He wiped a tear from one enormous eye. \"Wait until I tell the fellows in the common room.\"\n\n\"I'm glad you find this amusing,\" Wren said flatly. \"Could you perhaps point me toward him?\"\n\n\"Third floor, east corridor, office at the end. But I should warn you—he's in the middle of his dissertation defense. Very tense. Very intense. Probably don't interrupt if you value your eyebrows.\"\n\n\"My eyebrows?\"\n\n\"Dragons can get a bit... combustible when stressed.\"\n\nWren considered this. Then she shrugged. \"I'll risk it.\"\n\nShe found the east corridor easily enough. It was lined with portraits of distinguished-looking dragons, each one labeled with a name, a title, and a list of academic achievements. She passed Cornelius the Wise (Emeritus Professor of Mineral Analysis), Cornelius the Learned (Chair of the Department of Igneous Rock Studies), and Cornelius the Pedantic (who apparently held seventeen degrees and wasn't done yet).\n\nAt the end of the corridor, a door stood slightly ajar. From within came the sound of voices—deep, rumbling voices, the kind that made the floor vibrate slightly.\n\n\"—and your analysis of the pyroclastic flow patterns is, frankly, UNCONVINCING.\"\n\n\"With respect, Professor Thornscale, I believe my data speaks for itself—\"\n\n\"Your DATA speaks of INSUFFICIENT FIELD SAMPLES. How many lava tubes did you actually survey?\"\n\n\"Forty-seven, but—\"\n\n\"FORTY-SEVEN? In a mountain range containing over THREE HUNDRED documented tubes? You call that comprehensive?\"\n\nWren pushed the door open.\n\nThe room was large—it had to be, to accommodate the five dragons currently occupying it. Four of them sat behind a curved table, looking stern and scholarly. The fifth stood at a podium covered in charts and geological diagrams, looking harassed.\n\nAll five dragons turned to stare at her.\n\n\"Um,\" Wren said. \"Is one of you Cornelius of the Ashenmount Estate?\"\n\nThe dragon at the podium raised one claw. \"That would be me. And you are...?\"\n\n\"Lady Wren Fitzgerald. Your fiancée, apparently.\"\n\nThe silence that followed was so complete that Wren could hear one of the charts rustling in a draft.\n\nThen Cornelius did something unexpected.\n\nHe fainted.\n\nIt was really more of a controlled collapse—three tons of dragon crumpling gracefully to the stone floor, charts scattering in all directions, one claw still raised in the air as if he'd been about to make a point.\n\nThe four dragons behind the table exchanged looks.\n\n\"This is most irregular,\" said the one who had been complaining about lava tubes. \"We're in the middle of a defense.\"\n\n\"My apologies,\" Wren said, not sounding apologetic at all. \"But I believe this takes precedence. We have a clerical situation.\"\n\n\"A clerical situation?\"\n\n\"I appear to be legally betrothed to your candidate due to a filing error seventeen years ago. We need to resolve this before my eighteenth birthday, which is in three weeks.\"\n\nOne of the other dragons—an elderly female with silver scales and an expression of weary amusement—began to laugh. It was a gentler sound than the receptionist's, more like distant thunder.\n\n\"Oh, this is marvelous,\" she said. \"Cornelius has been so smug about avoiding the Betrothal Office. Said they'd never catch up with him. Said his paperwork was impeccable.\" She looked down at the unconscious dragon with something approaching fondness. \"Serves him right.\"\n\nCornelius groaned.\n\n\"He's waking up,\" Wren observed. \"Perhaps we should give him a moment.\"\n\n\"Perhaps you should give us ALL a moment,\" the lava-tube dragon grumbled. \"We have a dissertation to evaluate.\"\n\n\"Your dissertation can wait,\" the silver dragon said firmly. \"This is far more interesting.\" She turned to Wren with a smile that showed entirely too many teeth. \"I am Professor Emberheart, Dean of Academic Affairs. And I believe, young lady, that you have just made my century considerably more entertaining.\"\n\nCornelius sat up slowly. He was, Wren noted, a handsome dragon, if you were the sort of person who found dragons handsome. His scales were a deep copper color, like old pennies, and his eyes—now open and staring at her with a mixture of horror and confusion—were the same green-and-gold as a fire opal.\n\n\"This isn't happening,\" he said.\n\n\"I'm afraid it is.\"\n\n\"I filled out exemption forms. I filed deferral requests. I submitted seventeen appeals to the Office's Review Board.\"\n\n\"And yet here I am.\"\n\nCornelius put his head in his claws. \"My dissertation.\"\n\n\"Will have to wait,\" Professor Emberheart said cheerfully. \"I'm sure the committee can reconvene next month. In the meantime, it seems you have a betrothal to deal with.\"\n\n\"I don't WANT a betrothal. I want to finish my research. I want tenure. I want to spend the next fifty years studying volcanic mineral deposits in PEACE.\"\n\n\"I don't want a betrothal either,\" Wren said. \"I want to catalog beetles. But apparently neither of us gets what we want, because some clerk seventeen years ago couldn't be bothered to read a form properly.\"\n\nCornelius looked up at her. For a moment, they just stared at each other—a seventeen-year-old girl who would rather be studying insects, and a four-hundred-year-old dragon who would rather be studying rocks.\n\n\"This is absurd,\" Cornelius said.\n\n\"Yes,\" Wren agreed.\n\n\"We need to fix it.\"\n\n\"Obviously.\"\n\n\"There must be a way to dissolve the agreement.\"\n\n\"There is. We need to find someone named Ms. Parchment at the Royal Betrothal Office. She's the only one with the authority to approve a dissolution.\"\n\nCornelius brightened slightly. \"That doesn't sound too difficult.\"\n\n\"She's on vacation for three weeks.\"\n\nCornelius deflated.\n\n\"But,\" Wren continued, \"I'm not inclined to wait that long. Are you?\"\n\n\"Certainly not.\"\n\n\"Then we find her. She's visiting her sister in the Outer Isles. How hard can it be?\"\n\nCornelius stood up, his full height putting him at approximately three times Wren's size. \"The Outer Isles are remote, poorly mapped, and plagued by unpredictable weather.\"\n\n\"So?\"\n\n\"I'm simply pointing out the difficulties.\"\n\n\"Are you a scholar or aren't you? Consider it a field expedition.\" Wren smiled. \"Besides, I hear there are excellent beetles in the Outer Isles. Something about the volcanic soil.\"\n\nCornelius stared at her. Then, slowly, something that might have been respect crept into his expression.\n\n\"You're not what I expected,\" he said.\n\n\"Neither are you. I expected more fire-breathing and princess-eating.\"\n\n\"That's a vicious stereotype. I'm a vegetarian.\"\n\n\"Noted.\" Wren held out her hand. \"Partners, then? Until this mess is sorted?\"\n\nCornelius looked at her hand, then back at her face. After a moment, he extended one massive claw and very carefully shook it.\n\n\"Partners,\" he agreed. \"But I'm bringing my research notes.\"\n\n\"And I'm bringing my specimen jars.\"\n\n\"This,\" Professor Emberheart said, still watching with evident delight, \"is going to be magnificent.\"\n","narration":null},{"id":3,"number":3,"title":"The Knight Arrives","file":"chapter-3.md","markdown":"# The Knight Arrives\n\nThey were three hours into their journey to the Outer Isles when the knight appeared.\n\nWren had been riding on Cornelius's back, which was considerably faster than the carriage (Bernard had been sent home with a note for her parents, which simply read: \"Fixing the problem. Back soon. Don't worry. - W\"). The view from dragon-height was spectacular, and Wren had already spotted seventeen species of birds she'd never seen before. She was making notes in her field journal when she heard the horn.\n\n\"What's that?\" she asked.\n\nCornelius sighed. It was a massive exhalation that briefly warmed the air around them by several degrees. \"That,\" he said, \"would be trouble.\"\n\nBelow them, a figure on horseback was galloping along the road, blowing a horn with one hand and waving a sword with the other. He wore armor that gleamed in the sunlight and a helmet topped with an elaborate plume of feathers. He was also, Wren noticed, heading directly toward them.\n\n\"HALT, FOUL BEAST!\" the knight shouted. \"RELEASE THE MAIDEN!\"\n\n\"Oh, for the love of sedimentary rock,\" Cornelius muttered.\n\n\"Should we... stop?\"\n\n\"If we don't, he'll just keep following us. They always do.\" Cornelius began to descend, landing with surprising grace in a meadow beside the road. \"Fair warning: this might take a while.\"\n\nThe knight thundered up, his horse wheezing with exertion. He was, Wren observed, young—probably only a few years older than her—and extremely enthusiastic. His armor had been polished so aggressively that it was almost blinding.\n\n\"STAND ASIDE, MONSTER!\" he bellowed, pointing his sword at Cornelius. \"I, Sir Galahad Pemberton the Third, have come to rescue this fair maiden from your villainous clutches!\"\n\n\"I'm not clutching her,\" Cornelius said patiently. \"She's sitting on my back. There's a difference.\"\n\n\"You have KIDNAPPED her!\"\n\n\"I really haven't.\"\n\n\"I have DOCUMENTATION!\" Sir Galahad produced a scroll from somewhere in his armor and unfurled it dramatically. \"A formal complaint was filed with the Royal Knight's Guild! A damsel in distress! Abducted by a dragon! This is EXACTLY the sort of situation I am trained for!\"\n\nWren raised her hand. \"Excuse me?\"\n\nSir Galahad faltered slightly. \"Yes?\"\n\n\"I'm not in distress. And I haven't been abducted. We're traveling together voluntarily.\"\n\n\"But... but the documentation says...\"\n\n\"Let me see that.\" Wren slid off Cornelius's back and walked over to the knight. She took the scroll from his unresisting fingers and read it.\n\nOFFICIAL RESCUE REQUEST\nFiled by: Lady Fitzgerald (mother)\nNature of Emergency: Daughter has been TAKEN by a DRAGON\nDamsel Status: Very distressed (presumably)\nDragon Status: Evil (presumably)\nUrgency Level: MAXIMUM\n\n\"My mother filed this,\" Wren said flatly.\n\n\"Your mother cares about your safety!\"\n\n\"My mother cares about my birthday party not being ruined by a scandal.\" Wren handed the scroll back. \"There's been a misunderstanding. Cornelius and I are partners in a bureaucratic matter. We're going to find a clerk. There's no distress. There's no kidnapping. There's no need for a rescue.\"\n\nSir Galahad looked stricken. \"But... I rode all the way from the capital.\"\n\n\"I'm sorry about that.\"\n\n\"I polished my armor for THREE HOURS.\"\n\n\"It's very shiny,\" Wren acknowledged.\n\n\"I wrote a speech.\" He patted a pocket in his armor sadly. \"It was quite good. There was a bit about honor, and a bit about valor, and a part where I compared you to a rose among thorns.\"\n\n\"That sounds... nice.\"\n\n\"It RHYMED.\"\n\nWren felt, unexpectedly, a little sorry for him. He looked so deflated, sitting there on his exhausted horse with his polished armor and his useless speech. \"Look, Sir—what was it?\"\n\n\"Galahad. Sir Galahad Pemberton the Third.\"\n\n\"Right. Sir Galahad. I appreciate the effort, truly. But I don't need rescuing. What I need is to find a bureaucrat.\"\n\nSir Galahad's brow furrowed beneath his visor. \"A bureaucrat?\"\n\n\"Her name is Ms. Parchment. She works at the Royal Betrothal Office. She's currently on holiday in the Outer Isles, and we need to find her so she can dissolve an erroneous betrothal agreement.\"\n\n\"The betrothal is between her and me,\" Cornelius added. \"Which neither of us wants. So we're trying to fix it.\"\n\n\"You're betrothed? To HIM?\"\n\n\"Clerical error,\" Wren said. \"Long story.\"\n\nSir Galahad sat in silence for a moment, processing this information. Then, slowly, his expression brightened.\n\n\"So the dragon ISN'T villainous?\"\n\n\"He's a geology scholar. He's writing a dissertation on volcanic mineral deposits.\"\n\n\"And you AREN'T being held against your will?\"\n\n\"I'm searching for beetles. Voluntarily.\"\n\n\"And the whole situation is just... paperwork?\"\n\n\"Essentially.\"\n\nSir Galahad removed his helmet, revealing a face that was younger than Wren had expected—freckled and earnest and currently working through some complicated emotions. \"This is... this is not at all what I was trained for.\"\n\n\"What WERE you trained for?\" Cornelius asked, with what might have been genuine curiosity.\n\n\"Dragons. Evil ones. Who kidnap maidens. Who need to be defeated in single combat.\" He gestured vaguely with his sword. \"There's usually a battle. Sometimes fire. Always a grateful damsel who needs escorting home.\"\n\n\"That sounds exhausting,\" Wren said.\n\n\"It IS exhausting. And terrifying. And honestly, I'm not very good at it.\" Sir Galahad slumped in his saddle. \"I've been a knight for two years and I haven't rescued anyone. This was supposed to be my first real quest. My father was a knight. And his father. And HIS father. All the way back to the original Sir Galahad Pemberton, who rescued TWELVE maidens in a single afternoon.\"\n\n\"That seems like a lot of maidens,\" Cornelius observed.\n\n\"It was a very busy afternoon. Apparently there was a discount on kidnappings that week.\"\n\nWren and Cornelius exchanged looks.\n\n\"Sir Galahad,\" Wren said slowly. \"What would you rather be doing? If you weren't a knight?\"\n\nThe question seemed to catch him off guard. \"What do you mean?\"\n\n\"I mean, if you could do anything. If your father and grandfather and great-great-great-grandfather weren't all watching. What would you choose?\"\n\nSir Galahad was quiet for a long moment. Then, very softly, he said: \"Flowers.\"\n\n\"I'm sorry?\"\n\n\"I'd grow flowers. I'd have a little shop somewhere quiet, where nobody was trying to kill me or set me on fire or write songs about my heroic deeds. I'd have window boxes with petunias. I'd learn which soils work best for roses. I'd...\" He trailed off, looking embarrassed. \"It's stupid.\"\n\n\"It's not stupid,\" Wren said. \"It's what you want.\"\n\n\"Wants don't matter. Not for Pembertons. We're knights. We've ALWAYS been knights. The armor has been in my family for seven generations.\" He gestured at himself. \"It doesn't even fit properly. I have to stuff socks in the boots.\"\n\nCornelius cleared his throat. \"I couldn't help but notice that you seem reluctant to actually fight me.\"\n\n\"What?\"\n\n\"When you rode up, you waved your sword around, but you never actually... attacked. You just sort of pointed at things and shouted.\"\n\nSir Galahad's face went red. \"I was... working up to it.\"\n\n\"Were you?\"\n\n\"The shouting is an important part. You have to establish dominance.\"\n\n\"You were stalling.\"\n\n\"I was NOT stalling, I was—\" He stopped. His shoulders dropped. \"I was absolutely stalling. I'm terrified of dragons. I'm terrified of combat. I'm terrified of HORSES, frankly, and I've been riding one for two years. I'm the worst knight in the history of the Pemberton family, and that includes Great-Uncle Reginald, who once challenged a windmill to a duel and LOST.\"\n\n\"Then why do you keep doing it?\" Wren asked.\n\n\"Because I don't know how to stop! The Guild has expectations! My family has expectations! There are QUOTAS, do you know that? Every knight is supposed to complete at least three rescues a year. I've done NONE. They're going to revoke my certification!\"\n\nWren looked at Cornelius. Cornelius looked at Wren.\n\n\"Sir Galahad,\" Wren said. \"What if I told you there might be a way to get out of the knight business? Legally and officially, with proper paperwork?\"\n\nHis eyes widened. \"Is that possible?\"\n\n\"It might be. The woman we're looking for, Ms. Parchment, handles all sorts of official dissolutions. Betrothals, contracts, professional certifications...\" She glanced at Cornelius. \"Maybe even knight registrations?\"\n\n\"The Outer Isles,\" Cornelius mused. \"Known for their flowers.\"\n\n\"Excellent volcanic soil,\" Wren added. \"Very good for petunias.\"\n\nSir Galahad looked between them, hope dawning on his face like a very confused sunrise. \"You think... you think she could help me?\"\n\n\"I think it's worth asking.\" Wren climbed back onto Cornelius's back. \"What do you say? Want to join a quest to find a bureaucrat?\"\n\nSir Galahad straightened in his saddle. For a moment, he looked almost like a real knight—determined, courageous, ready for adventure. Then he sneezed, because he was allergic to his own horse, and the moment was somewhat ruined.\n\n\"Yes,\" he said, wiping his nose. \"Yes, I would like that very much.\"\n\n\"Then let's go.\" Wren looked down at his exhausted horse. \"Can that animal keep up with a dragon?\"\n\n\"Probably not.\"\n\n\"He can ride with us,\" Cornelius offered, somewhat grudgingly. \"If he promises not to point any swords at me.\"\n\nSir Galahad sheathed his sword immediately. \"Done.\"\n\n\"And if he stops calling me 'foul beast.'\"\n\n\"Also done. What should I call you?\"\n\n\"Cornelius. I have a doctorate.\"\n\n\"Dr. Cornelius it is.\"\n\nAnd so their party grew to three: a girl who loved beetles, a dragon who loved rocks, and a knight who secretly loved flowers. They made an unlikely team. They made an even more unlikely rescue squad.\n\nBut then again, nobody was being rescued.\n\nNot yet, anyway.\n","narration":null},{"id":4,"number":4,"title":"The Bureaucrat's Quest","file":"chapter-4.md","markdown":"# The Bureaucrat's Quest\n\nThe Outer Isles were, as Cornelius had warned, poorly mapped. This was putting it generously. The map they had obtained from a fisherman on the coast contained approximately four islands, a sea serpent (labeled \"Here Be Stanley\"), and the encouraging note \"Probably More Islands Around Here Somewhere.\"\n\n\"This is useless,\" Sir Galahad said, peering at it.\n\n\"It's not useless. It's... interpretive.\" Wren turned the map sideways. \"I think this squiggle might be Ms. Parchment's sister's island. Or possibly a coffee stain.\"\n\nThey were standing on the deck of a ferry that serviced the outer islands, or at least the ones that the ferry captain remembered existed. The captain herself was a weathered woman named Captain Marlowe who had been sailing these waters for forty years and still managed to get lost on a weekly basis.\n\n\"You want the Parchment cottage?\" Captain Marlowe had said when they boarded. \"Oh, that's on Gull Island. Or was it Tern Island? Something with birds. Lots of bird islands out there. Very popular with birds, the Outer Isles.\"\n\n\"Do you know which bird, specifically?\" Wren had asked.\n\n\"Definitely a seabird. Probably.\"\n\nThis was the level of precision they were working with.\n\nCornelius was not on the ferry. He was flying alongside it, keeping a respectful distance so as not to alarm the other passengers (of which there were three: an old man who was asleep, a woman with a basket of fish, and a goat, which was technically cargo but had refused to go below deck).\n\n\"Tell me more about Ms. Parchment,\" Sir Galahad said, still studying the map as if it might suddenly become helpful. \"What's she like?\"\n\n\"I've never met her. I only know she's the Senior Clerk at the Royal Betrothal Office, and she's the only one authorized to approve dissolutions.\" Wren watched a seagull fight another seagull for a scrap of bread. The seagulls in the Outer Isles were particularly aggressive. \"The lawyers said she was 'very particular about forms.'\"\n\n\"What does that mean?\"\n\n\"Probably that she likes things done properly.\"\n\n\"I like things done properly,\" Sir Galahad said earnestly. \"I always polish my armor before a quest. And I organize my swords by length.\"\n\n\"How many swords do you have?\"\n\n\"Twelve. It's a family tradition. One for each maiden Sir Galahad the First rescued.\"\n\n\"That's a lot of swords for someone who doesn't like fighting.\"\n\nSir Galahad looked uncomfortable. \"I mostly just... dust them.\"\n\nThe ferry lurched suddenly, and Captain Marlowe's voice rang out: \"Found it! Definitely bird island! See all the birds?\"\n\nThere were, indeed, a lot of birds. The island rising from the mist ahead was absolutely covered in them—gulls and terns and puffins and several species Wren couldn't identify. The air was thick with cries and calls and the general chaos of avian society.\n\n\"That's a lot of birds,\" Sir Galahad said faintly.\n\n\"This doesn't narrow it down,\" Wren muttered. \"EVERY island here probably has birds.\"\n\nBut as the ferry drew closer, she spotted something promising: a small cottage perched on a cliff, with a neat garden and a sign by the door. Even from this distance, she could see that the sign was organized, labeled, and extremely official-looking.\n\n\"That's the place,\" she said with certainty. \"Nobody else would have a sign that bureaucratic.\"\n\nThey disembarked on a small dock that swayed alarmingly under their feet. Cornelius landed nearby, scattering birds in all directions and earning a reproachful look from the woman with the fish basket.\n\n\"Sorry,\" he said. \"I tried to be quiet.\"\n\nThe path to the cottage wound up through the bird-covered rocks. It was paved with precisely cut stones, each one level with the next. The garden they passed was organized by color AND by species AND by height, with small labels at the base of each plant indicating its Latin name and optimal watering schedule.\n\n\"This woman is very organized,\" Sir Galahad observed.\n\n\"This woman is TERRIFYINGLY organized,\" Cornelius corrected. \"I respect it.\"\n\nThe door of the cottage opened before they could knock, and a woman appeared. She was small, gray-haired, and wearing spectacles that magnified her eyes to an unsettling degree. She looked at them—the teenage girl, the knight with socks stuffed in his boots, and the three-ton dragon—with an expression of profound resignation.\n\n\"You're from the Office, aren't you,\" she said. It wasn't a question.\n\n\"Not exactly,\" Wren began.\n\n\"It's ALWAYS the Office. I take ONE vacation in fifteen years, and somehow the Office finds me. Do you know how far the Outer Isles are? Do you know how hard it was to get here? I had to take THREE ferries and a fishing boat and at one point I rode a dolphin, and STILL the Office finds me.\"\n\n\"We're not from the Office, exactly,\" Wren tried again. \"We're... clients. With a problem.\"\n\n\"Everyone has a problem. That's why I went on vacation. To GET AWAY from the problems.\" Ms. Parchment folded her arms. \"Whatever it is, it can wait until I'm back in the capital. I have a schedule. The schedule says I'm on holiday for three more weeks. The schedule does not say 'entertain random visitors with problems.'\"\n\n\"Please,\" Wren said. \"It's urgent. I'm betrothed to a dragon by mistake, and I need—\"\n\n\"Betrothed to a—\" Ms. Parchment's eyes went wide behind her spectacles. \"The Fitzgerald girl? THAT case?\"\n\n\"You know about it?\"\n\n\"Of COURSE I know about it. I'm the Senior Clerk. I know about EVERYTHING. The Fitzgerald case has been sitting in my 'urgent' pile for seventeen years.\" She paused. \"Which, now that I say it out loud, doesn't sound very urgent. But bureaucracy moves slowly. These things take time.\"\n\n\"Seventeen years is a lot of time,\" Cornelius pointed out.\n\n\"You're the dragon.\" Ms. Parchment studied him with professional interest. \"Cornelius of Ashenmount. Dissertation on volcanic minerals. Applied for seventeen extensions to your betrothal review. All denied.\"\n\n\"I was hoping you hadn't received those.\"\n\n\"I receive EVERYTHING.\" She turned back to Wren. \"And you. Lady Wren Fitzgerald. Seventeen years old. Ranked fourteenth in eligibility. Known for\"—she paused, consulting some mental file—\"correcting people about beetles at parties.\"\n\n\"I've gotten better about that.\"\n\n\"Hmm.\" Ms. Parchment looked between them. Then she looked at Sir Galahad, who was trying very hard to be invisible. \"And who's this? Another betrothal problem?\"\n\n\"Career dissolution, actually,\" Sir Galahad said quietly. \"I'd like to stop being a knight.\"\n\n\"Pemberton family?\"\n\n\"Yes.\"\n\n\"Third generation?\"\n\n\"Seventh, technically.\"\n\nMs. Parchment made a sound that might have been a laugh. \"The Pembertons. Always with the knights. Your great-great-grandfather submitted a resignation request once, you know. Said he wanted to become a candlestick maker. His family had him committed.\" She shook her head. \"The paperwork for THAT was a nightmare.\"\n\n\"Is there any way you could help us?\" Wren asked. \"I know you're on holiday, but—\"\n\n\"On holiday. Yes. AWAY from the Office. AWAY from the paperwork. AWAY from the seventeen piles of urgent cases that have been sitting on my desk for decades because the junior clerks can't find the right forms.\" Ms. Parchment's eye twitched. \"Do you have any idea how many forms there are in the Royal Betrothal Office? Four thousand, two hundred, and seventy-three. And that's not counting the subsections. Or the amendments. Or the special appendices for cases involving non-human parties.\"\n\n\"That... does sound like a lot,\" Wren admitted.\n\n\"It IS a lot. And I've memorized them all. Every single one. Form 27-B for standard dissolutions. Form 114-J for cross-species betrothals. Form 892-M for retroactive nullification of clerical errors. Form 17-X for—\" She stopped. Blinked. \"Wait.\"\n\n\"What?\"\n\n\"Form 17-X.\" Ms. Parchment's expression changed. \"The Ambiguity Clause. I haven't thought about that one in years.\"\n\n\"What's Form 17-X?\" Cornelius asked.\n\n\"It's... obscure. Very old. Rarely used. But it might...\" She trailed off, staring into the middle distance. \"The original betrothal document. Do you have a copy?\"\n\n\"No, but the Office should have the original.\"\n\n\"Hmm.\" Ms. Parchment was quiet for a long moment. The birds screamed around them. The wind ruffled her organized garden. Finally, she sighed.\n\n\"Come inside,\" she said. \"I need to review some things. And I suppose you'd all like tea.\"\n\n\"You're going to help us?\" Wren asked, hardly daring to believe it.\n\n\"I'm going to LOOK at the case. That's not the same as helping.\" Ms. Parchment turned back toward her cottage. \"But I admit, the Ambiguity Clause possibility is... intriguing. I do love a good bureaucratic loophole.\"\n\n\"She loves loopholes,\" Sir Galahad whispered to Wren. \"That seems like a good sign.\"\n\n\"She also called my father's resignation request a 'nightmare,'\" Wren whispered back. \"So let's not get too excited.\"\n\nThey followed Ms. Parchment into the cottage, which was exactly as organized as Wren had expected. Every book was alphabetized. Every tea cup was labeled. Every chair had a small sign indicating its optimal weight capacity.\n\n\"Sit,\" Ms. Parchment commanded. \"And tell me everything. From the beginning. And for the love of proper documentation, don't skip any details.\"\n\nSo Wren told her everything. The birthday invitations. The lawyers. The journey to Ashenmount. The fainting dragon. The knight with flowers in his heart. All of it.\n\nWhen she finished, Ms. Parchment was silent for a very long time.\n\n\"Form 17-X,\" she said finally. \"Yes. That might actually work.\"\n\n\"What does it do?\" Cornelius asked.\n\nMs. Parchment smiled. It was a small smile, barely there, but it was the first one they'd seen from her.\n\n\"Come back tomorrow,\" she said. \"I need to send for some files. And then, I think, we're going to have a very interesting conversation about the name 'Cornelius.'\"\n\n\"The name?\"\n\n\"Just come back tomorrow. And bring documentation. ALL of it.\"\n\nShe showed them to the door and closed it firmly behind them.\n\nOutside, the birds continued their endless screaming. The wind continued to blow. And somewhere, in a pile of paperwork that had been sitting untouched for seventeen years, an answer was waiting to be found.\n\n\"Well,\" said Sir Galahad. \"That went better than I expected.\"\n\n\"Did it?\" Wren asked.\n\n\"Nobody tried to set anyone on fire. I count that as a win.\"\n\nCornelius snorted, releasing a small puff of smoke. \"The day is young.\"\n","narration":null},{"id":5,"number":5,"title":"The Forms","file":"chapter-5.md","markdown":"# The Forms\n\nThey returned to Ms. Parchment's cottage the next morning to find the door open and the entire front room transformed into what could only be described as a war room for paperwork.\n\nFiles were everywhere. Stacked on tables, spread across the floor, pinned to the walls. Red string connected various documents in ways that seemed meaningful only to Ms. Parchment, who stood in the center of it all like a general surveying her battlefield.\n\n\"Come in,\" she said without turning around. \"Watch your step. Don't touch anything. And for the love of proper filing, don't BREATHE on the 1847 documents—they're extremely fragile.\"\n\nWren carefully navigated around a pile of yellowed papers. \"You've been busy.\"\n\n\"I haven't slept. I had a dolphin bring me files from the Office's auxiliary storage facility.\" Ms. Parchment turned to face them, and Wren saw that her eyes were slightly manic behind her spectacles. \"Do you know what I found?\"\n\n\"Something good?\" Sir Galahad asked hopefully.\n\n\"Something FASCINATING.\" Ms. Parchment grabbed a document from the nearest pile and thrust it at Wren. \"This is the original betrothal filing. Look at it. LOOK at it carefully.\"\n\nWren looked. It was a standard form—boxes and lines and official stamps—but the handwriting was almost illegible. \"I can barely read this.\"\n\n\"That's because Marmaduke Pennywhistle the Younger had terrible penmanship. But look HERE.\" Ms. Parchment pointed at a specific box. \"The betrothed party field. What does it say?\"\n\nWren squinted. \"'Cornelius of Ashenmount Estate.' That's what we already knew.\"\n\n\"Yes, but look at what it DOESN'T say.\" Ms. Parchment's smile was almost feral. \"There's no species designation. No title. No identifying numbers. Just 'Cornelius of Ashenmount Estate.'\"\n\n\"So?\"\n\n\"SO, young lady, this creates what we in the bureaucracy call a 'fatal ambiguity.'\" Ms. Parchment began pacing, stepping over files with the ease of long practice. \"The form ASSUMES that the betrothed party is clearly identified. But 'Cornelius of Ashenmount' is not a clear identification. It's practically MEANINGLESS.\"\n\nCornelius raised a claw. \"I beg your pardon. I'm Cornelius of Ashenmount.\"\n\n\"Yes, YOU are. But you're not the only one.\"\n\n\"Well, yes, there are forty-seven Corneliuses at the university—\"\n\n\"I'm not talking about the university.\" Ms. Parchment grabbed another document. \"I'm talking about THIS.\"\n\nIt was a birth certificate, old but well-preserved. At the top, in elegant calligraphy, it read:\n\nPRINCE CORNELIUS MARCUS ASHWORTH\nBorn: Ashenmount Royal Estate\nTitle: Third in Line to the Throne of Ashenmount\n\nWren stared at it. \"There's a HUMAN prince named Cornelius? From the Ashenmount Estate?\"\n\n\"The Ashenmount Royal Estate is different from the Ashenmount Dragon Territory, but they share a name. A very old name. Goes back centuries. And seventeen years ago, when your betrothal was filed, there was indeed a human baby named Cornelius associated with Ashenmount.\"\n\n\"So the clerk might have meant—\"\n\n\"The clerk didn't specify WHICH Cornelius. The form just says 'Cornelius of Ashenmount Estate.' That could refer to the dragon Cornelius OR the human prince Cornelius. The paperwork doesn't clarify.\"\n\nCornelius sat down heavily, which caused several stacks of paper to flutter. \"Are you saying this entire situation is because of a NAMING coincidence?\"\n\n\"I'm saying it's because of inadequate documentation practices. But yes, essentially.\" Ms. Parchment looked almost gleeful. \"Form 17-X, the Ambiguity Clause, allows for the reinterpretation of betrothal agreements when the original filing contains a fatal ambiguity. If we can prove that 'Cornelius of Ashenmount' could reasonably refer to EITHER party, we can petition to have the betrothal reassigned.\"\n\n\"Reassigned to the prince,\" Wren said slowly. \"The human prince.\"\n\n\"Exactly.\"\n\n\"But wait.\" Sir Galahad was frowning. \"Wouldn't that just create a NEW problem? Now Lady Wren would be betrothed to some prince she's never met.\"\n\n\"A human prince,\" Ms. Parchment said. \"Which is what her parents presumably wanted in the first place. A traditional match. Nothing unusual. Nothing requiring special cross-species documentation.\"\n\n\"But I don't WANT to be betrothed to anyone,\" Wren protested. \"That's the whole point!\"\n\n\"Patience.\" Ms. Parchment held up another form. \"This is where it gets interesting. Prince Cornelius Ashworth is eighteen years old. He reached the age of majority three months ago. According to Betrothal Law, once a party reaches majority, they can formally contest any pre-arranged betrothal by filing a Form 88-C, the 'Mutual Dissolution by Consent of Both Parties.'\"\n\n\"So if the betrothal is transferred to the prince—\"\n\n\"And the prince agrees to dissolve it—\"\n\n\"Then it's over? Just like that?\"\n\n\"Just like that. Assuming, of course, that the prince cooperates.\" Ms. Parchment's expression sobered slightly. \"I don't know Prince Cornelius personally. He might be delighted to dissolve a surprise betrothal. Or he might be... less cooperative.\"\n\nWren thought about this. \"What do we know about him?\"\n\n\"Not much. The Ashworth royal family is relatively private. They control the Ashenmount region—the human parts, anyway. Moderate kingdom. Nothing particularly notable.\" Ms. Parchment shuffled through some papers. \"There ARE a few social notices. Apparently the prince is known for... ah.\"\n\n\"For what?\"\n\n\"For his interest in natural history.\"\n\n\"Natural history?\"\n\n\"Specifically entomology.\"\n\n\"Specifically WHAT?\"\n\n\"Bugs, dear.\" Ms. Parchment looked up with an expression that was almost amused. \"Prince Cornelius Ashworth is apparently quite passionate about bugs. Beetles in particular.\"\n\nThe silence that followed was profound.\n\n\"He collects beetles,\" Wren said.\n\n\"According to the society pages, yes. Caused quite a scandal when he skipped a royal ball to attend a lecture on dung beetles.\"\n\nCornelius made a sound that might have been a laugh. \"Well, well.\"\n\n\"This doesn't change anything,\" Wren said quickly. \"I'm not interested in being betrothed to ANYONE, beetle collector or otherwise.\"\n\n\"No, but it does suggest he might be sympathetic to your situation.\" Ms. Parchment began gathering documents into a neat stack. \"Someone who prefers bugs to balls might understand someone who prefers beetles to betrothals.\"\n\n\"So what's the plan?\" Sir Galahad asked. \"We go find the prince?\"\n\n\"You go find the prince,\" Ms. Parchment confirmed. \"You explain the situation. You get him to sign the Form 88-C. You bring it back to me, I file it, and this whole mess becomes a footnote in the Office's records.\" She paused. \"Well, a very LONG footnote. With multiple appendices. And probably its own filing cabinet.\"\n\n\"Where is Prince Cornelius now?\"\n\n\"The Ashenmount Royal Estate. About two days' travel from here, if you have a dragon.\" She gave Cornelius a meaningful look. \"You DO have a dragon.\"\n\n\"I'm not a mode of transportation,\" Cornelius grumbled. \"I'm a scholar.\"\n\n\"You're both. Most things in life are multiple things.\" Ms. Parchment handed Wren the stack of documents. \"Take these. You'll need them for the formal petition. Form 17-X, Form 88-C, copies of the original filing, the birth certificate, and my preliminary assessment. All properly notarized.\"\n\n\"You notarized them already?\"\n\n\"I notarized them SEVENTEEN years ago. I told you, I knew about this case. I've been waiting for someone to actually DO something about it.\" She allowed herself a small smile. \"I'm glad someone finally did.\"\n\nWren tucked the documents carefully into her specimen bag (which was surprisingly waterproof and organizationally sound). \"Thank you, Ms. Parchment. Truly.\"\n\n\"Don't thank me yet. The paperwork is only half the battle. You still need to convince a prince to give up a perfectly good betrothal.\"\n\n\"It's not a perfectly good betrothal. It's a clerical error.\"\n\n\"To you, it's an error. To someone else, it might be an opportunity.\" Ms. Parchment's expression was unreadable. \"Princes have been known to enjoy advantageous marriages. Even accidental ones.\"\n\n\"But you said he was interested in beetles—\"\n\n\"Interest in beetles does not preclude interest in politics. Just... be careful. Princes are unpredictable. Especially young ones.\"\n\nSir Galahad raised his hand. \"What about my situation? The knight thing?\"\n\nMs. Parchment sighed. \"One bureaucratic nightmare at a time, Sir Pemberton. Resolve the betrothal, then come back. I'll need to review three hundred years of Knight's Guild regulations to find a loophole for you.\"\n\n\"You'd do that?\"\n\n\"I'd do it because it would be INTERESTING. The Pemberton exemption clause has never been successfully invoked. It would be a professional challenge.\" She almost smiled. \"I do enjoy a professional challenge.\"\n\nThey said their goodbyes and left the cottage, documents in hand, destination clear.\n\n\"Two days to the Ashenmount Royal Estate,\" Wren said, looking at the sky. \"We should start now.\"\n\n\"Agreed.\" Cornelius stretched his wings. \"Though I have to say, the irony of this situation is not lost on me.\"\n\n\"What irony?\"\n\n\"I've spent four hundred years avoiding betrothals, and now my freedom depends on me helping to arrange one.\" He shook his great copper head. \"The universe has a strange sense of humor.\"\n\n\"At least you're not the one getting betrothed this time.\"\n\n\"True. That IS a significant improvement.\"\n\nSir Galahad climbed carefully onto Cornelius's back, settling behind Wren. \"To the prince, then?\"\n\n\"To the prince.\" Wren patted her specimen bag, feeling the reassuring weight of the documents inside. \"And hopefully, to the end of this ridiculous mess.\"\n\nCornelius launched into the sky, leaving the bird-covered island behind. Below them, in her meticulously organized cottage, Ms. Parchment was already starting a new file.\n\nShe labeled it: THE CORNELIUS AMBIGUITY.\n\nIt was going to be magnificent.\n","narration":null},{"id":6,"number":6,"title":"The Other Cornelius","file":"chapter-6.md","markdown":"# The Other Cornelius\n\nThe Ashenmount Royal Estate was not what Wren expected.\n\nShe had imagined something grand—towering spires, fluttering banners, guards in polished armor standing at attention. The usual royal nonsense. What she found instead was a sprawling manor house surrounded by gardens and greenhouses, with not a single banner in sight.\n\n\"Are you sure this is the place?\" Sir Galahad asked, squinting at the building.\n\n\"The sign says 'Ashenmount Royal Estate,'\" Cornelius observed. \"I would assume that's fairly conclusive.\"\n\nThe sign in question was small and tasteful, almost apologetic about announcing royalty. Next to it was a larger, more enthusiastic sign that read: ASHENMOUNT ENTOMOLOGICAL SOCIETY - VISITORS WELCOME.\n\n\"I think I like this prince already,\" Wren murmured.\n\nThey landed in what appeared to be a designated dragon landing zone (helpfully labeled as such), and were immediately greeted by a butler who showed no surprise whatsoever at their unusual party.\n\n\"Lady Wren Fitzgerald?\" the butler inquired. \"His Highness is expecting you.\"\n\n\"Expecting us?\"\n\n\"Word travels quickly. Ms. Parchment sent a courier dolphin. Very efficient creatures, dolphins.\" The butler gestured toward the manor. \"If you'll follow me? His Highness is in the east greenhouse. Something about a rare weevil delivery.\"\n\nThey followed the butler through the manor, which was decorated with an eclectic mix of royal portraits and mounted insects. A particularly impressive beetle specimen hung above the main staircase, framed in gold.\n\n\"Is that a *Dynastes hercules*?\" Wren asked, stopping to stare.\n\n\"Yes, my lady. His Highness caught it himself during an expedition to the Southern Continent. It remains one of his prized possessions.\"\n\n\"It's beautiful.\"\n\n\"He'll be pleased you think so. Most visitors just ask why there's a giant bug on the wall.\"\n\nThe east greenhouse was warm and humid, filled with tropical plants and the gentle sound of insects buzzing. In the center of it all, a young man with dark hair and dirt-smudged glasses was carefully transferring small beetles from a shipping container into a terrarium.\n\n\"Just a moment,\" he said without looking up. \"These little fellows are stressed from travel. They need gentle handling.\"\n\nWren found herself holding her breath as she watched him work. His movements were precise and careful, exactly the way she handled her own specimens. When the last beetle was safely in its new home, he straightened up and turned to face them.\n\nPrince Cornelius Ashworth was, objectively speaking, quite handsome. He had the kind of face that probably looked good on coins—strong jaw, clear eyes, a nose that suggested good breeding. But what Wren noticed most was that his fingernails had dirt under them and his shirt had a small tear at the cuff where something had clearly snagged it.\n\nHe looked, in other words, like someone who actually did things.\n\n\"Lady Wren Fitzgerald,\" he said, extending a hand. \"I've heard about your collection. The Fitzgerald beetle room is apparently legendary.\"\n\n\"You've heard about my beetles?\"\n\n\"The entomological community is smaller than you'd think. Word gets around.\" He smiled, and it was a genuine smile, not the practiced kind that royalty usually deployed. \"I understand we're accidentally betrothed?\"\n\n\"According to the paperwork, yes.\"\n\n\"How wonderfully absurd.\" He gestured toward a table with chairs. \"Sit, please. And perhaps explain how we're going to un-betroth ourselves? The dolphin message was somewhat vague.\"\n\nWren sat and began laying out the documents while Cornelius (the dragon) and Sir Galahad found spots around the periphery. The prince listened attentively as she explained the situation—the clerical error, the two Corneliuses, the Ambiguity Clause, and the mutual dissolution form.\n\n\"So you need me to sign this,\" the prince said, picking up Form 88-C, \"and the entire problem goes away.\"\n\n\"Essentially, yes.\"\n\n\"And you came all this way—tracked down a bureaucrat on vacation, deciphered a seventeen-year-old filing error, and convinced a dragon to give you a ride—just to ask me to sign a piece of paper?\"\n\n\"When you put it that way, it does seem rather simple.\"\n\nPrince Cornelius laughed. It was a nice laugh, warm and unexpected. \"Most people would have just waited for Ms. Parchment to come back from holiday.\"\n\n\"I'm not most people.\"\n\n\"No, you're clearly not.\" He set down the form and studied her with those clear eyes. \"Can I ask you something? Before I sign?\"\n\n\"Of course.\"\n\n\"Why beetles?\"\n\nIt was such an unexpected question that Wren actually had to think about it. \"What do you mean?\"\n\n\"I mean, you're nobility. You could do anything. Host parties. Commission portraits. Collect jewelry or horses or whatever it is noble ladies are supposed to collect. But you chose beetles. Why?\"\n\nWren was quiet for a moment. In the background, the beetles in the terrarium made soft rustling sounds.\n\n\"Because they're honest,\" she said finally. \"Beetles don't pretend to be anything they're not. They don't play politics or worry about rankings or care if you use the right fork at dinner. A beetle is just... a beetle. You can observe it, document it, understand it. There are rules—scientific rules—and if you follow them, you get truth. I like truth.\"\n\nPrince Cornelius nodded slowly. \"That's almost exactly what I would have said.\"\n\n\"Why beetles for you?\"\n\n\"Because they're the largest order of insects, representing about forty percent of all known insect species. They're the most successful life form on the planet, and most people barely notice them.\" He smiled. \"I like noticing things that other people overlook.\"\n\nThey sat in silence for a moment, two people who had accidentally discovered they understood each other.\n\n\"You know,\" the prince said, \"if we HAD been properly betrothed—intentionally, I mean—this might not have been terrible.\"\n\nWren felt her face grow warm. \"We've only just met.\"\n\n\"I know. I'm just observing.\" He picked up a pen. \"But I understand you want your freedom. You want to choose your own path. I respect that.\" He paused. \"I want the same thing, honestly. My parents have opinions about who I should marry, and none of their candidates have ever understood why there's a beetle over the main staircase.\"\n\n\"It's a magnificent specimen.\"\n\n\"Thank you. Caught it myself during—\"\n\n\"An expedition to the Southern Continent. Your butler mentioned.\"\n\nPrince Cornelius grinned. \"You were paying attention.\"\n\n\"I always pay attention to beetles.\"\n\nHe signed the form with a flourish and handed it back to her. \"There. Officially un-betrothed. You're free.\"\n\nWren looked at the signature, feeling an unexpected mix of relief and something else—something she couldn't quite name. \"Thank you.\"\n\n\"Thank YOU. This was the most interesting morning I've had in months.\" He stood and offered his hand again. \"Perhaps we could correspond? Compare notes on our collections? I'm working on a complete survey of Ashenmount's native ground beetles, and I'd love an outside perspective.\"\n\n\"I'd like that.\" Wren shook his hand, noting again the calluses and dirt. \"I'm particularly interested in the volcanic species. The ones that live near the hot springs.\"\n\n\"Oh, those are fascinating! The thermal tolerance adaptations alone—\" He caught himself, laughing. \"Sorry. I could talk about this for hours.\"\n\n\"So could I.\"\n\nThey looked at each other, and something passed between them—not romance, exactly, but recognition. The look of one dedicated oddball seeing another.\n\n\"Your dragon is very patient,\" the prince observed, glancing at Cornelius (who had fallen asleep on a patch of warm stones near the greenhouse heater).\n\n\"He's not MY dragon. We're just... traveling together.\"\n\n\"Still. It's not every day you see a dragon napping in a greenhouse.\"\n\nSir Galahad, who had been very quiet throughout this exchange, cleared his throat. \"If I might ask, Your Highness—do you know anything about the process for dissolving knight certifications? Hypothetically?\"\n\nThe prince raised an eyebrow. \"Tired of the knight business?\"\n\n\"Exhausted.\"\n\n\"There's a form for that. Form 445-K, I think. My cousin tried to resign from the Royal Guard once.\" He paused. \"He wasn't successful, but that was because he filled out the wrong form. The bureaucracy can be navigated, if you know how.\"\n\n\"We have a consultant,\" Wren said. \"Ms. Parchment.\"\n\n\"Oh, if you have Ms. Parchment, you're in good hands. She's legendary. They say she once found a loophole that dissolved an entire county. The county didn't technically exist anymore, so no one could be taxed for living there.\" The prince shrugged. \"The county is still there, of course. People still live there. They just don't have to pay taxes.\"\n\n\"That seems... problematic.\"\n\n\"That's bureaucracy for you. The forms create their own reality.\"\n\nWren tucked the signed document carefully into her specimen bag. \"We should go. Get this back to Ms. Parchment before anything else goes wrong.\"\n\n\"Wise.\" The prince walked them to the door. \"It was genuinely nice to meet you, Lady Wren. And you, Sir Galahad. And...\" He glanced at the still-sleeping dragon. \"Dr. Cornelius, I presume?\"\n\nCornelius opened one eye. \"You know, you could have mentioned earlier that there was another Cornelius of Ashenmount. Would have saved everyone a lot of trouble.\"\n\n\"We dragons don't interact much with the human nobility. And my parents don't exactly advertise our name—too many people asking if we're related to the dragons.\" The prince smiled. \"We're not, for the record. Just unlucky with geography.\"\n\n\"Noted.\" Cornelius stretched, standing and shaking off his nap. \"Ready to go?\"\n\n\"Ready.\" Wren paused at the door. \"I'll write to you. About the volcanic beetles.\"\n\n\"I look forward to it.\" Prince Cornelius's smile was warm. \"And Lady Wren? For what it's worth—I think you're going to have a wonderful eighteenth birthday. Now that you're not accidentally betrothed to anyone.\"\n\n\"Neither dragon nor prince.\"\n\n\"Neither dragon nor prince,\" he agreed. \"Just yourself. Which seems like more than enough.\"\n\nThey said their goodbyes and lifted off into the afternoon sky, the signed form tucked safely away, the tangled web of paperwork finally beginning to unravel.\n\nBehind them, in his greenhouse, Prince Cornelius Ashworth returned to his beetles with a smile on his face.\n\nHe would write to her first, he decided. No sense waiting.\n\nAfter all, good beetle correspondents were hard to find.\n","narration":null},{"id":7,"number":7,"title":"The Resolution","file":"chapter-7.md","markdown":"# The Resolution\n\nThree weeks later, Lady Wren Fitzgerald turned eighteen at a birthday celebration that was, by all accounts, significantly less complicated than anyone had feared.\n\nThe great hall of Fitzgerald Manor was decorated with flowers (provided by a new florist shop that had recently opened in the village), and the guest list had been revised to remove any dragons, much to Lady Fitzgerald's relief and Lord Fitzgerald's mild disappointment. (He had secretly been looking forward to meeting a dragon. They seemed interesting.)\n\nWren stood by the punch bowl, wearing a dress that her mother had insisted upon and that itched in at least fourteen places, watching the various nobles mingle and gossip. She was thinking about beetles.\n\nThis was not unusual. Wren was usually thinking about beetles.\n\n\"You could at least PRETEND to enjoy your own party,\" her mother said, appearing at her elbow.\n\n\"I'm enjoying it in my own way.\"\n\n\"Your own way involves staring into the middle distance and ignoring the Duke of Pemberton's very eligible son.\"\n\n\"Ah.\" Wren glanced across the room at the young man in question, who was attempting to look dashing and mostly succeeding. \"About that. You should know that the Pemberton family is going through some changes.\"\n\n\"Changes?\"\n\nAs if on cue, the doors to the great hall opened, and a most unusual party entered.\n\nSir Galahad Pemberton the Third came first—except he was no longer Sir Galahad. He was wearing simple clothes instead of armor, his hair was free of helmet-dent, and he was carrying an enormous bouquet of flowers that he had apparently grown himself.\n\nBehind him came Cornelius the dragon, who had to duck significantly to fit through the doorway and who was wearing, for reasons known only to himself, a small academic cap perched between his horns.\n\nAnd behind THEM came Ms. Parchment, clutching a folder of paperwork and looking like she was already mentally cataloging everything wrong with the hall's organizational structure.\n\nThe room went very quiet.\n\n\"Lady Wren,\" Sir Galahad announced, striding forward with a confidence he had never possessed as a knight. \"I come bearing flowers, as thanks for helping me find my true calling.\"\n\nHe presented the bouquet with a flourish. It was beautiful—roses and lilies and something purple that Wren didn't recognize.\n\n\"You're a florist now,\" she said.\n\n\"Officially, as of this morning. Ms. Parchment found the loophole.\" He beamed. \"The Pemberton Knight Exemption Clause of 1672, subsection 14, paragraph 3. If a Pemberton knight can demonstrate 'irreconcilable incompatibility with martial pursuits,' they can petition for release from family obligation. I submitted three years of evidence proving I'm absolutely terrible at being a knight.\"\n\n\"That must have been quite a lot of evidence.\"\n\n\"Seventeen pages. Single-spaced.\"\n\nLady Fitzgerald looked like she might faint. \"There's a dragon in my great hall.\"\n\n\"Yes, I apologize for that.\" Cornelius dipped his great head politely. \"I'm only here briefly. I wanted to deliver this.\" He extended one claw, in which he carefully held a small box.\n\nWren took it and opened it. Inside, nestled in velvet, was a beetle. Not a mounted specimen—a living one, with iridescent green wings that caught the light.\n\n\"It's a volcanic emerald beetle,\" Cornelius explained. \"They're only found in the hot springs of the Ashenmount Mountains. Very rare. Very beautiful. I thought, given our unusual acquaintance, you might appreciate it for your collection.\"\n\n\"It's incredible,\" Wren breathed. She could feel the tiny creature moving against her palm, warm and alive.\n\n\"Consider it a birthday gift. And also an apology for the whole betrothal confusion. That wasn't my fault, but I'm sorry nonetheless.\"\n\n\"Thank you.\" Wren looked up at him. \"What about your dissertation?\"\n\n\"Defended it last week. Passed with distinction.\" His dragon smile was surprisingly warm. \"Professor Emberheart said it was the most interesting defense she'd witnessed in two centuries. Apparently, having to postpone due to an accidental betrothal made for an excellent opening anecdote.\"\n\nMs. Parchment stepped forward, clearing her throat. \"If I might interrupt the sentimentality, I have paperwork to finalize.\" She produced a form from her folder. \"This is the official Certificate of Betrothal Dissolution, confirming that Lady Wren Fitzgerald is no longer legally betrothed to anyone—dragon, prince, or otherwise. I need a signature here, here, and initials here.\"\n\nWren signed. It felt, somehow, momentous—the end of a chapter that should never have been written in the first place.\n\n\"Additionally,\" Ms. Parchment continued, \"I'm pleased to inform you that the Royal Betrothal Office is implementing new policies as a result of this case. All future betrothals will require species verification, full legal name documentation, and at least THREE forms of identification.\" She looked almost satisfied. \"It's the most significant reform in two hundred years.\"\n\n\"You must be thrilled,\" Wren said.\n\n\"I am professionally fulfilled. Thrilled is for people who don't understand the gravity of proper documentation.\"\n\nLord Fitzgerald, who had been quietly watching all of this with an expression of bemused fascination, finally spoke up. \"I don't suppose, Dr. Cornelius, that you'd stay for the party? I've always wanted to speak with a dragon about... well, anything, really.\"\n\nCornelius considered this. \"I would need a larger chair.\"\n\n\"We have large chairs.\"\n\n\"And perhaps some rocks to eat. I'm fond of granite.\"\n\n\"We have granite in the garden. Decorative, but I'm sure it would be fine.\"\n\nLady Fitzgerald made a small noise of distress. Her husband ignored it.\n\n\"Then I would be honored,\" Cornelius said. \"I've never attended a human birthday celebration before.\"\n\n\"It's mostly standing around eating small foods and making conversation about nothing important,\" Wren told him.\n\n\"That sounds exactly like academic conferences. I'll feel right at home.\"\n\nThe party resumed, though it was significantly stranger than any party the Fitzgeralds had ever hosted. Cornelius proved surprisingly adept at small talk, especially with Lord Fitzgerald, who turned out to have a passionate interest in geology that he'd never been able to discuss with anyone. Sir Galahad—now just Galahad—spent the evening describing his plans for his flower shop to anyone who would listen, and found more enthusiasm than he had expected. Even Ms. Parchment relaxed enough to accept a cup of tea, though she spent most of the evening reorganizing the library's filing system because she \"couldn't bear to look at it.\"\n\nAs the evening wore on, Wren slipped out to the balcony for some fresh air. The moon was full, the garden was quiet, and the volcanic emerald beetle was safely in her pocket, wrapped in a handkerchief.\n\nShe heard footsteps behind her and turned to find her mother standing there, looking uncertain.\n\n\"I owe you an apology,\" Lady Fitzgerald said stiffly. Apologies did not come naturally to her. \"When I sent that knight after you—\"\n\n\"The knight worked out fine. He's a florist now.\"\n\n\"Yes, I noticed.\" Lady Fitzgerald was quiet for a moment. \"When I learned you were betrothed to a dragon, I panicked. All I could think about was the scandal, the gossip, what people would say. I didn't stop to consider that you might actually... handle it.\"\n\n\"I handled it.\"\n\n\"You did. Rather impressively.\" Her mother's expression softened, just slightly. \"You found a bureaucrat. You navigated an ancient loophole. You solved a seventeen-year-old clerical error. All while collecting beetles, apparently.\"\n\n\"I'm good at solving problems. When people let me.\"\n\nLady Fitzgerald nodded slowly. \"I'm beginning to understand that.\" She reached out and, awkwardly, patted Wren's shoulder. \"Happy birthday, Wren. I'm... proud of you.\"\n\n\"Thank you, Mother.\"\n\nHer mother went back inside. Wren stayed on the balcony, looking at the stars.\n\nShe was eighteen now. Officially an adult. Free from accidental betrothals and well-meaning interference. She could do anything she wanted.\n\nWhat she wanted, she realized, was to write a letter.\n\n*Dear Prince Cornelius,*\n\n*You were right about the volcanic species. The thermal tolerance adaptations are fascinating. I've been reading your paper on heat-resistant chitin, and I have questions. Many questions.*\n\n*Also, I have a new specimen. A volcanic emerald beetle, given to me by a dragon. I thought you might like to know it exists.*\n\n*I'm considering an expedition to the Southern Continent next year. I've heard there are beetles there that no one has properly cataloged. If you're interested in joining, I would welcome the company.*\n\n*No betrothals required.*\n\n*Your colleague in entomology,*\n*Lady Wren Fitzgerald*\n\n*P.S. - I've enclosed a sketch of the beetle. Notice the wing structure. It's unlike anything I've ever seen.*\n\nShe finished the letter late that night, after the guests had gone and the great hall was quiet. She sealed it with wax and addressed it to the Ashenmount Royal Estate.\n\nIn the morning, she sent it by courier.\n\nTwo days later, she received a reply.\n\n*Dear Lady Wren,*\n\n*I would be absolutely delighted to join your expedition. I've been looking for an excuse to visit the Southern Continent for years. My parents will disapprove, which makes it even more appealing.*\n\n*Your sketch is excellent. The wing structure suggests a previously unknown subspecies. We should discuss naming rights.*\n\n*I also have questions about your questions. Perhaps we should correspond more frequently.*\n\n*Perhaps we should correspond quite a lot.*\n\n*Your colleague in entomology (and adventures),*\n*Prince Cornelius Ashworth*\n\n*P.S. - The dragon stopped by yesterday. He wanted to tell me about a new mineral deposit he discovered. I think he was also checking up on me. Apparently, he feels responsible for our acquaintance.*\n\n*P.P.S. - He brought me a rock. I'm not sure what to do with it, but it was kind of him.*\n\nWren read the letter three times. Then she smiled, tucked it into her specimen journal, and began planning an expedition.\n\nShe was eighteen years old. She was officially un-betrothed. She had friends—a dragon, a former knight, and a prince who understood beetles.\n\nAnd somewhere out there, in the vast bureaucratic wilderness of the Royal Betrothal Office, her file had been permanently closed, stamped with the words: CASE RESOLVED - THE CORNELIUS AMBIGUITY.\n\nIt was, all things considered, a very good start.\n\nTHE END\n","narration":null}],"chapterCount":7,"audio":null,"narration":{"hasNarration":false,"chapters":[]},"assets":[],"standalone":false};
